The list above will be used when gathering card rates for standard cards. I did not include Promo cards (card provided in promotions such as special events) in the data I will be pulling. The main reason for this is because Promo cards obtained through events or special packs where there is a 100% chance of the card being obtained. I will, however, use the original card from '01 TCGPlayer Data Exploration' for tutorial consistency. I also really like the artwork and the price of the card/popularity of the Pokemon as been around the same for a while.

import requests as r
import json
import time
import datetime
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
from pandas.io.json import json_normalize

#url to post
action_postURL = 'https://infinite-api.tcgplayer.com/price/history/271837?range=annual'

#get data from that URL
res = r.get(action_postURL)

#put the data coming in from res into values as json
values = res.json()
In [16]:
#clean out any days that have no cards on the market
NumberOfDays= values['count']
dates = []
marketPrice = []
quantity = []
i = 0
while i < NumberOfDays:
    if int(values['result'][i]['variants'][0]['quantity']) > 0:
        dates.append(datetime.datetime.strptime(values['result'][i]['date'], '%Y-%m-%d'))
        marketPrice.append(float(values['result'][i]['variants'][0]['marketPrice']))
        quantity.append(int(values['result'][i]['variants'][0]['quantity']))
    i = i + 1
